+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JNRgiDDaihivbxywcXGcwv","type":"tool_result","content":"# Phase 1: Basic FIFO Queue\n\nImplement the core of the task queue: the ability to add tasks and retrieve them in first-in, first-out order.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- The queue should accept a payload (any data) when a task is added, and return a task object.\n- Each task must have a unique identifier (e.g., UUID), a status, and a creation timestamp.\n- New tasks start in a \"pending\" state.\n- Retrieving the next task should return the oldest pending task and transition it to a \"processing\" state.\n- If no tasks are available, retrieval should return `null`.\n- There should be a way to check how many tasks are waiting.\n# Phase 2: Named Queues\n\nExtend the system to support multiple independent queues, each identified by a name.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Tasks are added to a specific named queue. If no name is given, a default queue is used.\n- Each named queue operates independently -- adding to one does not affect another.\n- Retrieving a task pulls from the specified queue only.\n- Creating a queue happens implicitly when a task is first added to it.\n- There should be a way to list all queue names that exist.\n- Asking for a task from a non-existent or empty queue returns `null`.\n- The API should remain backward-compatible with Phase 1 (omitting the queue name uses the default).\n# Phase 3: Priority\n\nAdd priority support so that more urgent tasks are processed before less urgent ones.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Tasks can be assigned a priority level from 1 (highest) to 10 (lowest). The default priority is 5.\n- When retrieving the next task, higher-priority tasks (lower number) are returned first.\n- Tasks with the same priority are returned in FIFO order.\n- Invalid priority values (outside 1-10) should cause an error.\n- Priority operates per-queue -- each named queue maintains its own priority ordering.\n- The task object should expose its priority level.\n# Phase 4: Delayed and Scheduled Tasks\n\nAdd the ability to defer tasks so they only become available for processing after a specified time.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- A task can be given a delay (in milliseconds) or a specific future time at which it becomes available.\n- Delayed tasks are added to the queue immediately but are not returned when retrieving until their availability time has passed.\n- Non-delayed tasks are always preferred over delayed tasks that are not yet available.\n- When multiple delayed tasks become available simultaneously, they should be ordered by availability time, then priority, then FIFO.\n- The task object should indicate when it becomes available.\n- Delays work correctly with named queues.\n# Phase 5: Retry with Backoff\n\nAdd automatic retry functionality so that failed tasks can be re-attempted with increasing delays.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- There should be a way to mark a processing task as completed or failed.\n- When a task fails and has retries remaining, it is automatically re-added to the queue with a delay.\n- The delay follows exponential backoff: `baseDelay * 2^(attempt - 1)` (e.g., 1s, 2s, 4s, ...).\n- The default maximum number of retries is 3, but this should be configurable per task.\n- The base backoff delay defaults to 1000ms but should be configurable per task.\n- The task should track how many times it has been attempted.\n- Retried tasks keep their original queue and priority.\n- If all retries are exhausted, the task remains in a failed state.\n# Phase 6: Dead Letter Queue\n\nAdd a dead letter queue (DLQ) to capture tasks that have permanently failed after exhausting all retries.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- When a task has no more retries left, it is automatically moved to a dead letter queue associated with its original queue.\n- There should be a way to view all dead-lettered tasks for a given queue.\n- Dead-lettered tasks should retain their error information and a count of how many times they failed.\n- It should be possible to move a dead-lettered task back to its original queue for a fresh round of retries.\n- There should be a way to clear all dead-lettered tasks for a queue.\n- Each named queue has its own independent dead letter queue.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4b8303b8-8c3e-4855-9d5a-386b08b31c00","uuid":"f669342a-6a3c-4205-9fe3-3a9f407a9b25","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"# Phase 1: Basic FIFO Queue\n\nImplement the core of the task queue: the ability to add tasks and retrieve them in first-in, first-out order.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- The queue should accept a payload (any data) when a task is added, and return a task object.\n- Each task must have a unique identifier (e.g., UUID), a status, and a creation timestamp.\n- New tasks start in a \"pending\" state.\n- Retrieving the next task should return the oldest pending task and transition it to a \"processing\" state.\n- If no tasks are available, retrieval should return `null`.\n- There should be a way to check how many tasks are waiting.\n# Phase 2: Named Queues\n\nExtend the system to support multiple independent queues, each identified by a name.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Tasks are added to a specific named queue. If no name is given, a default queue is used.\n- Each named queue operates independently -- adding to one does not affect another.\n- Retrieving a task pulls from the specified queue only.\n- Creating a queue happens implicitly when a task is first added to it.\n- There should be a way to list all queue names that exist.\n- Asking for a task from a non-existent or empty queue returns `null`.\n- The API should remain backward-compatible with Phase 1 (omitting the queue name uses the default).\n# Phase 3: Priority\n\nAdd priority support so that more urgent tasks are processed before less urgent ones.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Tasks can be assigned a priority level from 1 (highest) to 10 (lowest). The default priority is 5.\n- When retrieving the next task, higher-priority tasks (lower number) are returned first.\n- Tasks with the same priority are returned in FIFO order.\n- Invalid priority values (outside 1-10) should cause an error.\n- Priority operates per-queue -- each named queue maintains its own priority ordering.\n- The task object should expose its priority level.\n# Phase 4: Delayed and Scheduled Tasks\n\nAdd the ability to defer tasks so they only become available for processing after a specified time.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- A task can be given a delay (in milliseconds) or a specific future time at which it becomes available.\n- Delayed tasks are added to the queue immediately but are not returned when retrieving until their availability time has passed.\n- Non-delayed tasks are always preferred over delayed tasks that are not yet available.\n- When multiple delayed tasks become available simultaneously, they should be ordered by availability time, then priority, then FIFO.\n- The task object should indicate when it becomes available.\n- Delays work correctly with named queues.\n# Phase 5: Retry with Backoff\n\nAdd automatic retry functionality so that failed tasks can be re-attempted with increasing delays.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- There should be a way to mark a processing task as completed or failed.\n- When a task fails and has retries remaining, it is automatically re-added to the queue with a delay.\n- The delay follows exponential backoff: `baseDelay * 2^(attempt - 1)` (e.g., 1s, 2s, 4s, ...).\n- The default maximum number of retries is 3, but this should be configurable per task.\n- The base backoff delay defaults to 1000ms but should be configurable per task.\n- The task should track how many times it has been attempted.\n- Retried tasks keep their original queue and priority.\n- If all retries are exhausted, the task remains in a failed state.\n# Phase 6: Dead Letter Queue\n\nAdd a dead letter queue (DLQ) to capture tasks that have permanently failed after exhausting all retries.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- When a task has no more retries left, it is automatically moved to a dead letter queue associated with its original queue.\n- There should be a way to view all dead-lettered tasks for a given queue.\n- Dead-lettered tasks should retain their error information and a count of how many times they failed.\n- It should be possible to move a dead-lettered task back to its original queue for a fresh round of retries.\n- There should be a way to clear all dead-lettered tasks for a queue.\n- Each named queue has its own independent dead letter queue.","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
